		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Combining Cultures: Free Peoples (Post Grima)<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.50)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1955'>Kyle "Master Kyle" McEachron</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1955&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> March 14, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> <br />
Well, honestly, there has been a lot of mixed feelings going around about Grima. Some say that he makes combining cultures a bad idea. That’s a myth. Since when did a limit of 3 (safely) make combining cultures a bad idea? With most decks, unless it is shire oriented, will say that there are really only 2 since Frodo counts. Here is one way around this.<br />
<br />
The ever popular, play monoculture. An obvious choice and I will leave it at that. But, that is obviously not our only choice. First thing is, since Shire is going to be one of your cultures, why not take advantage of it? You can use all the cards you want and it won’t endanger you. Sting and Oh Elbereth! are, once again, obvious choices. Merry, FTS is a good one. Anyways, you get my point, but since this article is about combining cultures, I won’t go into any more detail. Here are common myths that have come about as a result of Grima.<br />
<br />
Myth #1: Trust Me is Dead/ Gandalf is Dead<br />
I think it’s a safe bet to say that FotSF has probably turned in the towel, but the White Wizard doesn’t give up so easily. There is even more a reason to use our White friend, Rohan being the main one. Well then, I guess that means your 2 cultures would have to be Gandalf and Rohan. Well, Rohan is meant to be a stand alone culture, but Gandalf just sweetens the deal. The new skool Gandalf cards mainly rely on spotting twilight tokens. This was a problem before as it required the use of multiple expensive Gandalf events and flooding the pool, which isn’t such a great plan. Thankfully 3 new Rohirrim from BOHD (2 with G-Signets!) have arrived to solve our problem. Eowyn, Theoden, and Gamling all allow you to get twilight out there while still denying twilight for your opponent’s minions and not having to use multiple events. That way, you can get possessions on people without getting bombed, get Gandalf the twilight he needs, and even get some bonuses in the process. Fury of the White Rider is great Gandalf event, but requires there to be 3 twilight in the pool. Well, I guess I’ll play Herugrim and a Rider’s Mount on Theoden. Oh…look…there’s the twilight you need right there. The 3 added by the event + the 3 spotted will be more than enough for TWW to get his +3 strength bonus. As for Trust Me…Gandalf, Theoden, Eowyn. That’s your max 3 G-signets right there and that’s not even counting Frodo. As for Gandalf, by himself….don’t overlook the new Ents. More to come in EoF.<br />
<br />
Myth #2: Grima makes Smeagol Unplayable.<br />
Ahem, the correct phrase is ‘Grima makes Smeagol unsplashable’. Smeagol is a nice inclusion in any Ring-bound deck and don’t forget that Grima only targets unbound companions. Currently, though, there are only 3 cultures for Ring-bound so that’s not a problem as long as your unbounds are shire or Gondor. If your deck is exclusively ring-bound, you could even throw in Thrarin or Elf archer allys and Grima can’t do a thing about it. Smeagol was meant to be played in Ring-bound decks anyway. Old Noser will certainly aid the double move. Slinker will be a nice addition to Frodo/Sam Promise decks and even Ring-bound rangers (just make sure you can shed some burdens somehow). Of course, Smeagol is part of the companion count so adding him on can hurt you considering he is no stronger by himself than a hobbit. This is slightly offset by the fact that there are multiple ways of discarding him if his presence becomes a danger to you. <br />
<br />
Myth#3: The 3 Hunters is gone<br />
Assuming you used both unbound hobbits, 3 hunters would have been a 6 companion deck. With 6 companions, you have worse things to worry about than Grima anyways. Now, if you used only 2 of the hunters, then you are still ok. It’s just a matter of preference. Most decks will likely include Legolas, DH. Then you can choose whether you want to use Gimli or Aragorn. Aragorn allows the use of his bow, but Gimli is cheaper and allows Thrarin, who would normally be too risky, to be played. This also can compliment the use of My Axe is Notched and Final Count. Merry, FTS can be a great aid to those two winning skirmishes. <br />
<br />
Myth#4: Signet based decks are destroyed<br />
There have been rumors that a signet based deck is going to go down the hole because of Grima. I’ve already mentioned the above example of the G-signet seeing use without endangering you. The Frodo signet didn’t see a whole lot of action. Just the old weed strategy which used to involve the best Frodo signet companions. Greenleaf, HttWC, FoTSF, and, now, Faramir arrives to make it even stronger. Ok, but it is confined at the same time. Make use of the cultures you will undoubtedly use. These will be Shire and, most likely, Gondor as shire you must have and Gondor has 2 good Frodo signets. Well, for Shire, must I bring him up again…..Merry, FTS who happens to have the Frodo signet and would certainly be aided by Frodo’s Pipe. Also, the new BOHD signet double-wounder-for-lots-of-burdens card might be useful if you were using Gandalf’s pipe. This means that Gandalf would have to be your 3rd culture. The only Frodo Gandalf would only be 8 strength, so maybe waiting till EoF might be better for the use of that card.<br />
<br />
The Aragorn signet is the most difficult. Obviously, there are the 3 Hunters, but will likely be the 2 Hunters. Useful A-signets include KiE, Legolas, DH, Lockbearer, LoG, CoG, DoE etc…. Not outstanding choices, but with Hard Choice and perhaps some future support, this could be good, though not great at the moment. Just pick 2 cultures out those and go to work. <br />
<br />
Theoden signet has yet to evolve enough to have decks centered around it. <br />
<br />
Myth#5: Grima had a completely negative effect on the game<br />
 Think about it. Would you want to worry about Greenleaf, Aragorn’s bow, plus all the Rohan folk to worry about when playing shadow? Chances are, your minions won’t stand a chance, but with Grima, they do. Would you want your opponent to have 9 companions and be able to stop protect their best ones with Eowyn, LoR when your Enquea finally comes out? Chances are not. Would you want to face Defender +1 gorn, defender +1 super Eomer, Greenleaf, no skirmish Faramir, strength 12 gandalf, plus an empire of other seemingly unbeatable mains? I wouldn’t. You still have old options like Help in Doubt, Rohan and Elves, Ring-bound and Rohan among others. You cannot just cram them all into a super deck now. <br />
<br />
In conclusion, I hope this has answered some questions and has encouraged diversity again…or at least to realize that diversity is still out there, it just takes a more creative mind to find it.<br />
<br />
